04721nam a22005775i 9780228015185DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280151857 a10.1515/97802280151852doi  a(DE-B1597)655968  a(OCoLC)1324242930  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBR99.74b.G65 2022 7aREL0100002bisacsh04a261.5/62231 aGolan, Oren, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSacred Cyberspaces :bCatholicism, New Media, and the Religious Experience /cOren Golan, Michele Martini. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b24 photos, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAdvancing Studies in Religion ;v1300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tDigital Faith: Emerging Agents and Technologies for Devout Publics -- tDigital Religion and Global Publics -- tThe Rise of the Religious Webmaster: A Comparative Perspective -- tHoly Land YouTube Videos: The Visual Language of Religious Outreach -- tDigital Gates to the Holy Land: Mediatizing the Religious Experience -- tNetworking the Sacred for Global Publics: New Media Strategies for a Re-enchanted World -- tBolstering Religious Authority through Visual Content -- tVirtual Authenticity: Livestreaming Religious Sites -- tThe Pope on Instagram: Managing Religious Authority and Globalized Charisma in the Digital Age -- tConclusion: Catholicism, Rupture, and Media Efforts -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years every major institution has had to adapt to the fast-evolving technologies of the digital age or risk being left behind. Amid a global crisis of faith and declining levels of religious participation in places around the world, the Catholic Church has likewise come face to face with the challenges and possibilities of new media. Sacred Cyberspaces reveals how long-standing conflicts over power, influence, and legitimacy within religious organizations are being waged in the digital realm. Oren Golan and Michele Martini describe the tensions that arise as religious groups seek to reach the faithful in online spaces where traditional clerical authorities have less expertise and control. Focusing on the Catholic world, they examine the rise of devotional digital entrepreneurship and the roles of lay religious webmasters: the video makers, app developers, and web designers who devote their lives to evangelization and who literally run the show. The book also explores the nature of religious experience as it pivots to online platforms: cyberculture, prayer, ceremonies, pilgrimage, proselytization, and the relation to the transcendental.From live-streaming at world-famous sites in the Holy Land to the Instagram feed of Pope Francis, Sacred Cyberspaces evaluates the contemporary media strategies of the Catholic Church and sheds light on the future of religion online.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunicationxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aCyberspacexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aDigital mediaxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aExperience (Religion). 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh1 aMartini, Michele, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801518540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228015185423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97802280